	   <a name=104317364962030></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104317364962030><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>RE: Sks</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=145263><span id=Scholar>lunaticfringesk</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>275 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jan 21st 1:56 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.46]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>As a lvl 49 SK, I definitely wouldnt consider starting over just to reallocate your starting bonus points.&nbsp;&nbsp;Granted, if you wanted to maximize your advantage, then allocation of points might become important.  At the end of the day, however, your starting bonus points just arent THAT important.  You can definitely still make a hell of a character, even if you assigned all of your bonus points to a really *important* stat like CHA.<br><br>For non-ogre and troll classes:<br><br>In regards to INT, the only time I would ever recommend putting all bonus points into INT is if you honestly project to take this SK all the way up to 65 and get into a *uber* guild that will be doing lots of high-end encounters (beyond NToV and such; like Luclin bosses and beyond).  Even though it is debateable, there are some valid arguments to putting all bonus points into INT.  The default stat should probably be STA, which could still be the right answer even if you do plan on raiding with a high end guild.<br><br>(Ogres and trolls should put all, or substantially, all bonus points into INT at inception, regardless of intention in the future)<br><br>One other thing to note.  Mana pool doesnt mean a whole lot (save for high-end raiding situations); mana REGEN is vastly more important.  For the most part, all that having a larger mana pool really means is a longer period of time to med to full.  Dont get caught up into thinking that 49 and beyond you need a ton of INT because the spells take lots of mana.  While the mana cost does generally go up as the character level goes up, mana regen doesnt.  Therefore, dont sweat INT (if you are a small race; you will be fine)<br><br>Of course, having a large mana pool certainly is better than having a small mana pool, but it just isnt that big a deal, especially with C3/4/5 out there.  Want to make a big difference?  Get gear with FT on it, or bot a chanter that can constantly cast some form of mana regen on you, or get mental clarity from your aa abilities.  Those all help mana regen, which will make your life a lot easier than a large mana pool ever could.<br><br>Luna<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
